	  <title>Equivalent Hyperplanes - Examples</title>
	  <caption>Equivalent Hyperplanes - Examples</caption>
	
	  <showme>
		    <statement.showme>
			      <para>
            <para.body>Determine if the equations below are equivalent.</para.body>
         </para>
			      <math.array column="3">
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>2x + 3y - z</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>1</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>4x + 6y - 2z</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>2</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
         </math.array>
		    </statement.showme>
		    <answer.showme type="Solution">
         <answer.showme.block>
            <answer.showme.block.body>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>We notice that multiplying the first equation by <math>
                        <latex>2</latex>
                     </math> yields the second equation. So each solution of one of these equations is also a solution of the other. Therefore their solution sets form the same hyperplane in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                     </math>: the hyperplane perpendicular to <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{n}:=(2,3,-1)</latex>
                     </math> passing through <math>
                        <latex>(0,0,-1)</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
		          </answer.showme.block.body>
         </answer.showme.block>
      </answer.showme>
	  </showme>
	
	
	  <showme>
		    <statement.showme>
			      <para>
            <para.body>Determine if the equations below are equivalent.</para.body>
         </para>
			      <math.array column="3">
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>3s + 4t -u+v</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>1</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>9s + 12t - 3u + 3v</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>5</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
         </math.array>
		    </statement.showme>
		    <answer.showme type="Solution">
         <answer.showme.block>
            <answer.showme.block.body>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>We notice that multiplying the left hand side of the first equation by <math>
                        <latex>3</latex>
                     </math> yields the left hand side of the second equation. However, multiplying the right hand side of the first equation by <math>
                        <latex>3</latex>
                     </math> yields <math>
                        <latex>3\neq 5</latex>
                     </math>. Therefore it is not the case that one equation is a nonzero multiple of the other: the equations are not equivalent.</para.body>
               </para>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>So </para.body>
               </para>
		          </answer.showme.block.body>
         </answer.showme.block>
      </answer.showme>
	  </showme>
